Media notes: Zoomed in. It's resting after a very stressful incident this morning. It tried to fledge, but its foot was tangled in the fur from the nest cup, leaving it dangling from the entrance hole until I noticed and intervened.
Observation Details: The single nestling tried to fledge this morning, but its foot had gotten tangled in the fur of the nest cup, so it was dangling from the entrance hole of the box until I noticed and intervened. Its leg was badly skinned from rubbing against the entrance hole as it had struggled to fly away. Put it back in the box to rest, and it has stayed there all morning. It couldn't really move its injured leg, and I'm wondering if it's weak from being tangled in the nest lining for who knows how long.  (It did manage to properly fledge and perch well enough to move through the trees later in the day).

Observation Details: This bird was accidently left an orphan in its nest, which was an old woodpecker's hole, after we had a dead tree cut down on our property. It was naked except for a bit of fluff on top of its head, it did not appear to have eyelids yet and it could barely make a noise. Though it was weak by the time we realized what had happened, it pulled through unlike the other two siblings who unfortunately didn't make it. Thankfully, "Pip-Squeak" as we have named it, progressed quickly after a month and one week of constant and ongoing care starting which started May 7, 2022.   As of today, June 13, "Pip" is now able to fly around the room without running into things most of the time, has reached the height of at least eight feet off the ground and is sometimes eating on its own, but seems to still prefer to be handfed. Also, Pip does not like to be left alone and will call the moment you leave the room until you come back.   Thankfully it naturally learned to drink water on its own, but everything else has been a real learning curve. We started off on commercial formula, moved to mealworms and today was the first time it ate seeds of its own accord as it has rejected them each time they were offered until now. Also, it took to the taste of peanut butter after a while, but so far isn't inclined to eat suet unless there is an additional amount of peanut butter on top and still it only seems interested in limited amounts.  I've been playing all kinds of audio recordings from this website to Pip-Squeak as it's grown because I had no idea what kind of bird it was in the beginning, but overtime and with a lot of research I narrowed it down to Oak Titmouse recordings because it seems to identify with them the most and the sounds Pip makes so far are very similar, though not as complex yet. Also, I have made many video and audio recordings of Pip, sometimes with sounds of other birds playing in the background via online as it seemed to stimulate Pip to talk and other times this wasn't necessary as Pip started to chatter to itself after a while.  There is only one sound I can't seem to catch and that is due to timing issues. Sometimes Pip lets out a victorious sounding call after its flown around the room and landed successfully, other times it doesn't. I never know when it's going to make this sound but it's very distinct from the other calls so I'll keep trying to catch it before it's time to release Pip back into the wild.   Overall I'd say this is a very social bird with loads of curiosity. I've given it lots of different objects to investigate and even though it's easily frightened, Pip quickly calms when spoken to and can even handle a little loud rebuke from time to time as I tire of it pecking on my computer screen that it's so fond of sitting on now.   There are two main aspects I'd say that are particular about this bird. One was the odd pooping routine it had when it was very little, similar to that of a chickadee and now that it's grown it seems to enjoy picking its toes often and tapping on hard objects. I've heard that these birds eat acorns in the wild so perhaps this is just part of its process to achieving that goal in the future. Dovecry55

Observation Details: This bird was accidently left an orphan in its nest, which was an old woodpecker's hole, after we had a dead tree cut down on our property. It was naked except for a bit of fluff on top of its head, it did not appear to have eyelids yet and it could barely make a noise. Though it was weak by the time we realized what had happened, it pulled through unlike the other two siblings who unfortunately didn't make it. Thankfully, "Pip-Squeak" as we have named it, progressed quickly after a month and one week of constant and ongoing care starting which started May 7, 2022.   As of today, June 13, "Pip" is now able to fly around the room without running into things most of the time, has reached the height of at least eight feet off the ground and is sometimes eating on its own, but seems to still prefer to be handfed. Also, Pip does not like to be left alone and will call the moment you leave the room until you come back.   Thankfully it naturally learned to drink water on its own, but everything else has been a real learning curve. We started off on commercial formula, moved to mealworms and today was the first time it ate seeds of its own accord as it has rejected them each time they were offered until now. Also, it took to the taste of peanut butter after a while, but so far isn't inclined to eat suet unless there is an additional amount of peanut butter on top and still it only seems interested in limited amounts.  I've been playing all kinds of audio recordings from this website to Pip-Squeak as it's grown because I had no idea what kind of bird it was in the beginning, but overtime and with a lot of research I narrowed it down to Oak Titmouse recordings because it seems to identify with them the most and the sounds Pip makes so far are very similar, though not as complex yet. Also, I have made many video and audio recordings of Pip, sometimes with sounds of other birds playing in the background via online as it seemed to stimulate Pip to talk and other times this wasn't necessary as Pip started to chatter to itself after a while.  There is only one sound I can't seem to catch and that is due to timing issues. Sometimes Pip lets out a victorious sounding call after its flown around the room and landed successfully, other times it doesn't. I never know when it's going to make this sound but it's very distinct from the other calls so I'll keep trying to catch it before it's time to release Pip back into the wild.   Overall I'd say this is a very social bird with loads of curiosity. I've given it lots of different objects to investigate and even though it's easily frightened, Pip quickly calms when spoken to and can even handle a little loud rebuke from time to time as I tire of it pecking on my computer screen that it's so fond of sitting on now.   There are two main aspects I'd say that are particular about this bird. One was the odd pooping routine it had when it was very little, similar to that of a chickadee and now that it's grown it seems to enjoy picking its toes often and tapping on hard objects. I've heard that these birds eat acorns in the wild so perhaps this is just part of its process to achieving that goal in the future. Dovecry55
